  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some tips to potty train a puppy?",
  "response": "Potty training a puppy requires patience, consistency, and positive reinforcement. Here are some tips to help make the process smoother:\n\n### 1. **Establish a Routine**\n   - Take your puppy outside frequently, especially after:\n     - Waking up\n     - Eating or drinking\n     - Playing\n     - Napping\n   - Puppies usually need to go every 1-2 hours, depending on their age and breed.\n\n### 2. **Choose a Designated Potty Spot**\n   - Pick a specific area outside where you want your puppy to go. Consistently taking them to the same spot helps them associate that area with potty time.\n\n### 3. **Use a Cue Word**\n   - Use a consistent word or phrase (e.g., \"Go potty\") to signal that it\u2019s time to go. Repeat this word while they\u2019re doing their business to help them associate the word with the action.\n\n### 4. **Reward Success**\n   - Immediately praise and reward your puppy with treats, pets, or verbal praise when they go potty in the right spot. Positive reinforcement encourages them to repeat the behavior.\n\n### 5. **Supervise Closely**\n   - Keep an eye on your puppy indoors to catch signs they need to go (e.g., sniffing, circling, or whining). If you see these signs, take them outside right away.\n\n### 6. **Crate Training**\n   - Use a crate to help with potty training. Dogs naturally avoid soiling their sleeping area. Ensure the crate is the right size\u2014just big enough for your puppy to stand, turn around, and lie down comfortably.\n   - Take your puppy outside as soon as you let them out of the crate.\n\n### 7. **Limit Water Before Bed**\n   - Reduce water intake 1-2 hours before bedtime to minimize nighttime accidents.\n\n### 8. **Clean Accidents Thoroughly**\n   - If your puppy has an accident indoors, clean it up immediately with an enzymatic cleaner to remove odors that might attract them to the same spot again.\n\n### 9. **Be Patient and Consistent**\n   - Accidents are normal and part of the learning process. Avoid punishment, as it can create fear and hinder progress.\n\n### 10. **Gradually Extend Time Between Potty Breaks**\n   - As your puppy grows and gains better bladder control, slowly increase the time between potty breaks.\n\n### 11. **Track Progress**\n   - Keep a log of when your puppy eats, drinks, and goes potty to identify patterns and help you anticipate when they\u2019ll need to go.\n\nBy staying consistent and positive, your puppy will learn where and when it\u2019s appropriate to go potty.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
